<div style="position:absolute;left:66.72px;top:556.44px" class="cls_011"><span class="cls_011">*up is optional</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:41.76px;top:573.18px" class="cls_014"><span class="cls_014">**In the past tense, </span><span class="cls_015">IT ENDED UP </span><span class="cls_051">THAT s</span><span class="cls_015"> </span><span class="cls_014">and</span><span class="cls_015"> IT TURNED OUT </span><span class="cls_051">THAT s</span><span class="cls_014"> are variations of this pattern.</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:69.77px;top:585.84px" class="cls_014"><span class="cls_014">It ended up that he lost all his money.</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:288.73px;top:585.84px" class="cls_014"><span class="cls_014">It turned out she really didn't want to go there with him.</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:69.77px;top:598.43px" class="cls_014"><span class="cls_014">How did it end up?</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:288.72px;top:598.43px" class="cls_014"><span class="cls_014">How did it turn out?</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:36.72px;top:611.09px" class="cls_014"><span class="cls_014">- </span><span class="cls_015">JUST ABOUT, NEARLY </span><span class="cls_014">and </span><span class="cls_015">ALMOST</span><span class="cls_014"> mean the same. These are qualifiers that can be used with all the</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:36.72px;top:623.75px" class="cls_014"><span class="cls_014">above patterns except for KEEP and CONTINUE in the </span><span class="cls_015">past tense</span><span class="cls_014">.</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:63.73px;top:636.41px" class="cls_014"><span class="cls_014">He is </span><span class="cls_015">just about </span><span class="cls_014">ready to go.</span></div>
