<div style="position:absolute;left:251.64px;top:48.78px" class="cls_003"><span class="cls_003">I ONLY </span><span class="cls_056">v</span><span class="cls_003">.</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:36.72px;top:105.48px" class="cls_002"><span class="cls_002">1.  Other patterns with the same meaning are </span><span class="cls_011">I JUST </span><span class="cls_053">v</span><span class="cls_002"> and </span><span class="cls_011">ALL I DO IS </span><span class="cls_053">v</span><span class="cls_002"> on pages 42 and 43.</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:36.72px;top:133.08px" class="cls_002"><span class="cls_002">2.  </span><span class="cls_011">I DO NOTHING BUT </span><span class="cls_053">v</span><span class="cls_011">.</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:59.22px;top:146.88px" class="cls_002"><span class="cls_002">This is another variation of </span><span class="cls_011">I ONLY </span><span class="cls_053">v</span><span class="cls_011">.</span><span class="cls_002"> There is no question form and isn't usually used in the future</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:60.72px;top:160.68px" class="cls_002"><span class="cls_002">tense. In the past tense, DO changes to DID. DOES is used in the third person singular in the present</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:60.72px;top:174.48px" class="cls_002"><span class="cls_002">tense. This pattern usually implies that you are dissatisfied with what the person did.</span></div>
