<div style="position:absolute;left:172.38px;top:17.34px" class="cls_004"><span class="cls_004">LA BONTE’S TOP 100 ENGLISH CONVERSATION PATTERNS</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:557.58px;top:17.22px" class="cls_011"><span class="cls_011">69</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:36.72px;top:34.80px" class="cls_002"><span class="cls_002">Many sentences use ABOUT, FOR, etc. to join two different verbs or adjectives. If you want to use a</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:36.72px;top:48.60px" class="cls_002"><span class="cls_002">noun or object pronoun which is different than the subject of the sentence, generally the noun or object pronoun</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:36.72px;top:62.40px" class="cls_002"><span class="cls_002">is found directly in front of the verb. In the negative sentence, it is found in front of NOT. The exception to this</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:36.72px;top:76.20px" class="cls_002"><span class="cls_002">is "TO </span><span class="cls_054">v</span><span class="cls_002">" where the noun or object pronoun come before TO in the positive sentence.</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:36.72px;top:103.92px" class="cls_053"><span class="cls_053">PATTERN</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:144.72px;top:103.92px" class="cls_053"><span class="cls_053">POSITIVE</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:311.22px;top:103.92px" class="cls_053"><span class="cls_053">NEGATIVE</span></div>
