<div style="position:absolute;left:260.34px;top:62.58px" class="cls_003"><span class="cls_003">WHEN </span><span class="cls_056">s</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:230.34px;top:90.18px" class="cls_003"><span class="cls_003">WHEN </span><span class="cls_056">v</span><span class="cls_003">ING*</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:72.72px;top:133.08px" class="cls_002"><span class="cls_002">* The subject of both parts of the complex sentence/question have to be the same.</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:108.72px;top:146.88px" class="cls_002"><span class="cls_002">When studying, she listens to the radio.</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:108.72px;top:160.68px" class="cls_002"><span class="cls_002">When </span><span class="cls_011">she</span><span class="cls_002"> studies,</span><span class="cls_011"> she</span><span class="cls_002"> listens to the radio.</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:42.72px;top:174.48px" class="cls_002"><span class="cls_002">1. </span><span class="cls_011">WHEN </span><span class="cls_053">v</span><span class="cls_011">ING</span><span class="cls_002"> is not usually used with a negative sentence, the past tense or with an adjective.</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:42.72px;top:188.28px" class="cls_002"><span class="cls_002">2.  Below are some more specific variations of </span><span class="cls_011">WHEN s</span><span class="cls_002">.  </span><span class="cls_054">v</span><span class="cls_002">ING is not used.</span></div>
