<div style="position:absolute;left:231.84px;top:48.78px" class="cls_003"><span class="cls_003">AFTER </span><span class="cls_056">s</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:201.84px;top:76.38px" class="cls_003"><span class="cls_003">AFTER </span><span class="cls_056">v</span><span class="cls_003">ING*</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:90.72px;top:133.08px" class="cls_002"><span class="cls_002">* The subject of both parts of the complex sentence/question are the same.</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:180.72px;top:146.88px" class="cls_002"><span class="cls_002">After eating, they want to go dancing.</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:180.72px;top:160.68px" class="cls_011"><span class="cls_011">They</span><span class="cls_002"> want to go dancing after</span><span class="cls_011"> they</span><span class="cls_002"> eat.</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:36.72px;top:174.48px" class="cls_002"><span class="cls_002">1.  </span><span class="cls_011">AFTER </span><span class="cls_053">v</span><span class="cls_011">ING </span><span class="cls_002">is not usually used with a negative sentence, the past tense or with an adjective.</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:36.72px;top:202.08px" class="cls_002"><span class="cls_002">2.  A</span><span class="cls_011">FTERWARDS </span><span class="cls_053">s/q</span><span class="cls_011">.  </span><span class="cls_002">Note how this short form is used below. People understand what you</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:540.80px;top:202.08px" class="cls_002"><span class="cls_002">are</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:36.72px;top:215.88px" class="cls_002"><span class="cls_002">referring to when you use this short form.  AFTERWARDS</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:341.98px;top:215.88px" class="cls_002"><span class="cls_002">=  AFTER THAT</span></div>
