<div style="position:absolute;left:36.73px;top:506.32px" class="cls_014"><span class="cls_014">4.</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:56.01px;top:506.32px" class="cls_014"><span class="cls_014">The opposite of A LOT is A FEW or SOME. A FEW can't be used with TIME. A LITTLE can only</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:75.26px;top:518.98px" class="cls_014"><span class="cls_014">be used with TIME</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:72.73px;top:531.64px" class="cls_014"><span class="cls_014">She has</span><span class="cls_015"> a few</span><span class="cls_014"> things to eat.</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:322.04px;top:531.64px" class="cls_014"><span class="cls_014">He had</span><span class="cls_015"> a few</span><span class="cls_014"> places to show her.</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:72.73px;top:544.30px" class="cls_014"><span class="cls_014">They have </span><span class="cls_015">a little</span><span class="cls_014"> time to talk with you.</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:322.09px;top:544.30px" class="cls_014"><span class="cls_014">We had </span><span class="cls_015">some</span><span class="cls_014"> places to see.</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:36.73px;top:556.96px" class="cls_014"><span class="cls_014">5.  Use </span><span class="cls_015">FOR </span><span class="cls_051">n/op</span><span class="cls_014"> if you have two subjects in the sentence or question of any of the above patterns in</span></div>
<div style="position:absolute;left:75.24px;top:569.64px" class="cls_014"><span class="cls_014">"a, b, c or d".</span></div>
